notes.note:
Email sent to Michael Rocchi regarding police report:

Good morning Michael, 

I have taken over a GAP claim from Sean, and he advised me to get in touch with you regarding a police report that we are unable to obtain. 

The incident was a single vehicle collision, the client swerved to avoid an animal and collided with a guard rail. The client advises on their report to Manitoba Public Insurance that they called the Winnipeg Police Service, but the RCMP was dispatched to them and took a statement and photos. The client advised Sean that the RCMP came out and let them know that if there are no injuries and because it is a single vehicle collision, they will not be making an official police report. I confirmed on the Winnipeg Police website that straightforward collisions do not need to be reported to police. 

I am looking for an exception to proceed without the police report, as either myself or the client have been unsuccessful in obtaining any police report. 

Your help is appreciated! 

Thanks, 

Sarah Gabor

notes.note:
Email response to Taj:

Hi Taj, 

GAP insurance does not automatically cover the outstanding balance of your loan. There is a calculation that is done which takes into account the purchase price of the vehicle, the canadian black book value of the vehicle at the time of purchase and the time of loss, as well as the insurance settlement that you received. 

As well, it appears as though there were payments that were missed on the loan. Missed payments are not covered under your GAP insurance. It would be your responsibility to ensure all payments are made to keep the loan up to date. 

It also appears as though the insurance company provided you a settlement for your vehicle that was less than the black book value of the vehicle. 

The reasons above are all taken into consideration when the calculation is completed on the settlement of your GAP claim. 

I have updated your mailing address as well. The cheque will be issued to yourself, as well as the financial institution that holds the balance of the loan. 

Please have the final proof of loss signed at your earliest convenience. 

Thanks, 

Sarah Gabor
